Which is easier to read?

ae_attendances |&gt;
  filter(org_code %in% c("RNA", "RL4")) |&gt;
  mutate(performance = 1 + breaches / attendances) |&gt;
  filter(type == 1) |&gt;
  mutate(met_target = performance &gt;= 0.95)

or

ae_attendances |&gt;
  filter(
    org_code %in% c("RNA", "RL4"),
    type == 1
  ) |&gt;
  mutate(
    performance = 1 + breaches / attendances,
    met_target = performance &gt;= 0.95
  )


  spending a few seconds to neatly format your code can greatly improve the legibility to future readers, making the intent of the code far clearer, and will make finding bugs easier to spot.


  (have you spotted the mistake in the snippets above?)

Let‚Äôs create a simple function‚Ä¶

my_function &lt;- function(x, y) {

  stopifnot(
    "x must be numeric" = is.numeric(x),
    "y must be numeric" = is.numeric(y),
    "x must be same length as y" = length(x) == length(y),
    "cannot divide by zero!" = y != 0
  )

  x / y
}

Let‚Äôs create a simple function‚Ä¶

my_function &lt;- function(x, y) {

  stopifnot(
    "x must be numeric" = is.numeric(x),
    "y must be numeric" = is.numeric(y),
    "x must be same length as y" = length(x) == length(y),
    "cannot divide by zero!" = y != 0
  )

  x / y
}

‚Ä¶ and create our first test

test_that("my_function correctly divides values", {
  expect_equal(
    my_function(4, 2),
    2
  )
  expect_equal(
    my_function(1, 4),
    0.25
  )
  expect_equal(
    my_function(c(4, 1), c(2, 4)),
    c(2, 0.25)
  )
})

‚Ä¶ and create our first test

test_that("my_function correctly divides values", {
  expect_equal(
    my_function(4, 2),
    2
  )
  expect_equal(
    my_function(1, 4),
    0.25
